I had high expectation and enthusiasm based on the raves and how difficult it is to make reservation to dine here. I'm very sad to say that I was disappointed and not sure if it was a bad night but I've had a lot better food in many other places but I was glad I got to experience the dining here and "check it off the list." Thank to my credit card concierge service, the arranged the reservation two months in advance an scored us a 6pm reservation. It took about 3 hours for the whole dining (not because we were slow eater or there were lots to eat.. but because service was choppy and got slower by the course). We left the restaurant past 9pm. We both went with the 5 courses, but I opted to skip the dessert (since it was our anniversary and I knew they would give us a dessert)....This later I kinda regret since dessert turned out to be the BEST course among all other items that we ordered. The free item that day was this one-bite piece of bread topped with caramelized eggplant. It was alright, a bit too sweet for my liking, my hubby enjoyed it more than I did. For appetizers, I opted for the seared Foie Gras and hubby opted for the crab risotto. Both items were delicious, though not spectacular. The foie gras tasted fresh and perfectly cooked and the Risotto was creamy, cheesy, rich with lots of crab meat and the portion was very generous. Smaller stomach could probably get filled up by just eating the free bread+butter and the risotto. For seafood course, I opted for the Lobster while hubby opted for the coconut seafood curry rice. The lobster was fresh and delicious. I loved the potato pureed, it was perfectly seasoned, creamy, rich, a great complement to the lobster. I was very happy with this dish! Hubby's coconut curry had LOTS of seafood, I tasted the scallops and it melted in my mouth, very sweet, and not overly cooked. This dish was delicious but it was a bit difficult for me to taste any curry flavor, though the overall was delicious and I appreciate the freshness of the ingredients... I wouldn't call this a curry dish. For the meat course, I opted for the Duck Breast, Lamb and Stuffed Quail. Hubby's opted for the fillet of beef and Bison. The duck breast....the duck itself was fresh and good quality. One would thought they were eating red meat...I never had a duck taste this way and I was impressed. However, the endive that came with the dish, killed my tastebud with the bitterness... I had a small bite and I didn't eat the rest. The other components to the duck was just alright and all had one dimensional flavor (lacking umami) that after a while you get bored eating. Hubby's fillet of beef was perfectly cooked and very very very tender. I loved his dish more than mine... The lamb, was also perfectly cooked and it was not gamey, one could easily mistaken the flavor of the meat as it was beef. Again, it was a bit blah and I didn't think the farro accompanying this dish added anything exciting. The bison was VERY chewy and tough.... very disappointed with this dish and hubby did too. Yes, bison tends to be leaner but other bison steak we had was definitely a lot more tender than the one served here :( The biggest disappointment to me was the stuffed quail... it boasted how it was stuffed with fancy things (mushrooms, foie gras) but yet the flavor was just flat...the stuffing was very peppery ..the corn muffin that came with the dish was delicious though. For dessert, hubby ordered the Louisiana Buttercake!!! We couldn't have made a better choice! it was probably one of the BEST desserts I've had. It was warm, chewy, buttery, not overly sweet, soooo good! get this!!! They presented us with chocolate mousse for our anniversary along with the tiny cookie treats...they were all delicious but didn't top the Buttercake! Now, service was friendly but the timing of when the food arrived at our table got VERY VERY VERY slow after the seafood dish. We waited about 15-20 minutes after we finished and licked clean our plates before the next dish arrived... This caused our meal to go on for 3 hours.. a bit much and you just lost that "excitements" of eating and we started to get full.. though we continued eating without taking anything home...They also did not check on us during the meal, though the water-gal kept refilling our glasses. In conclusion.. I checked it off my list to experience dining here.. but not sure I'll come back, I'll try other places to spend money and splurge. The food is just not that great, so so.

Also, we were sandwiched between other people and could hear their conversations perfectly. That ruined our whole dining experience. Not sure if I would come back. La Folie over GD any day.

    I had high expectation and enthusiasm based on the raves and how difficult it is to make reservation to dine here. I'm very sad to say that I was disappointed and not sure if it was a bad night but I've had a lot better food in many other places but I was glad I got to experience the dining here and "check it off the list."

    Thank to my credit card concierge service, the arranged the reservation two months in advance an scored us a 6pm reservation. It took about 3 hours for the whole dining (not because we were slow eater or there were lots to eat.. but because service was choppy and got slower by the course). We left the restaurant past 9pm.

    We both went with the 5 courses, but I opted to skip the dessert (since it was our anniversary and I knew they would give us a dessert)....This later I kinda regret since dessert turned out to be the BEST course among all other items that we ordered.

    The free item that day was this one-bite piece of bread topped with caramelized eggplant. It was alright, a bit too sweet for my liking, my hubby enjoyed it more than I did.

    For appetizers, I opted for the seared Foie Gras and hubby opted for the crab risotto. Both items were delicious, though not spectacular. The foie gras tasted fresh and perfectly cooked and the Risotto was creamy, cheesy, rich with lots of crab meat and the portion was very generous. Smaller stomach could probably get filled up by just eating the free bread+butter and the risotto.

    For seafood course, I opted for the Lobster while hubby opted for the coconut seafood curry rice. The lobster was fresh and delicious. I loved the potato pureed, it was perfectly seasoned, creamy, rich, a great complement to the lobster. I was very happy with this dish! Hubby's coconut curry had LOTS of seafood, I tasted the scallops and it melted in my mouth, very sweet, and not overly cooked. This dish was delicious but it was a bit difficult for me to taste any curry flavor, though the overall was delicious and I appreciate the freshness of the ingredients... I wouldn't call this a curry dish.

    For the meat course, I opted for the Duck Breast, Lamb and Stuffed Quail. Hubby's opted for the fillet of beef and Bison.
    The duck breast....the duck itself was fresh and good quality. One would thought they were eating red meat...I never had a duck taste this way and I was impressed. However, the endive that came with the dish, killed my tastebud with the bitterness... I had a small bite and I didn't eat the rest. The other components to the duck was just alright and all had one dimensional flavor (lacking umami) that after a while you get bored eating. Hubby's fillet of beef was perfectly cooked and very very very tender. I loved his dish more than mine...
    The lamb, was also perfectly cooked and it was not gamey, one could easily mistaken the flavor of the meat as it was beef. Again, it was a bit blah and I didn't think the farro accompanying this dish added anything exciting.
    The bison was VERY chewy and tough.... very disappointed with this dish and hubby did too. Yes, bison tends to be leaner but other bison steak we had was definitely a lot more tender than the one served here :(
    The biggest disappointment to me was the stuffed quail... it boasted how it was stuffed with fancy things (mushrooms, foie gras) but yet the flavor was just flat...the stuffing was very peppery ..the corn muffin that came with the dish was delicious though.

    For dessert, hubby ordered the Louisiana Buttercake!!! We couldn't have made a better choice! it was probably one of the BEST desserts I've had. It was warm, chewy, buttery, not overly sweet, soooo good! get this!!! They presented us with chocolate mousse for our anniversary along with the tiny cookie treats...they were all delicious but didn't top the Buttercake!

    Now, service was friendly but the timing of when the food arrived at our table got VERY VERY VERY slow after the seafood dish. We waited about 15-20 minutes after we finished and licked clean our plates before the next dish arrived... This caused our meal to go on for 3 hours.. a bit much and you just lost that "excitements" of eating and we started to get full.. though we continued eating without taking anything home...They also did not check on us during the meal, though the water-gal kept refilling our glasses.

    In conclusion.. I checked it off my list to experience dining here.. but not sure I'll come back, I'll try other places to spend money and splurge. The food is just not that great, so so.

    1 check-in

    Classic perfection from start to finish.

    Gary Danko has truly nailed the three pillars of foodie bliss: 1) phenomenal service, 2) inviting ambiance, and 3) extraordinarily delicious food.

    The fiance surprised me with a spontaneous date night here recently and we were both beyond pleased with our experience. We both opted for the 5 course menu with wine pairings (the portions are quite healthy so it turned out to be very filling). Every single item that we ordered was top notch and absolutely delicious.

    The highlight was the cheese cart -- if you select cheese as one of your courses, your waiter will bring out a cart with 30+ cheeses from across the world, walk you through the nuances of each cheese, and then let you pick your favorite three. As an aspiring cheese connoisseur, I was beyond elated with this experience!

    The wine pairings were tres magnifique and accompanied each course flawlessly.

    Here were our favorite items from the menu: seared foie gras, risotto with rock shrimp, seared sea scallops, seared fillet of beef and the duck breast. We also loved the baked chocolate souffle!

    So on your next romantic date night or celebratory meal, do yourself a favor and pay Gary Danko a visit. You absolutely won't regret it.

    Happy Eating, Yelpers!
